      "content": "They would have framed it as a matter of prudent fiscal risk assessment, arguing that concentrated risk in certain areas threatened the stability of the entire lending market. Planners often spoke of maintaining \"community cohesion\" by ensuring homogenous property values, suggesting that mixed-income or racially diverse areas led to unpredictable depreciation. Furthermore, they claimed that targeted lending was simply a way to ensure that municipal resources and infrastructure investments were directed toward areas with the highest perceived capacity for repayment and civic order. This language masked prejudice by cloaking it in the jargon of sound urban finance and risk mitigation.",
