      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of this view argued that distinct cultural enclaves allowed for the preservation of unique traditions, preventing the dilution of specific ethnic or racial identities in a homogenized urban landscape. They posited that by maintaining separate spheres, communities could develop and reinforce their own internal social structures and customs without the perceived disruption of external influences. This separation was framed not as exclusion, but as a necessary mechanism for maintaining distinct cultural integrity and reducing the friction that they believed arose from forced integration. Therefore, they presented separation as a way to ensure cultural continuity and predictable social order within each defined group.",
